Governance Layer — Modular Design (v2)

Scope

In: enforce the approved business rules (block / approval-required / allow / field-masking) on every MCP tool call, with decision traces.
Explicitly out (for now): token validation / authN, OPA or any external policy engine, persisted approval workflow. The design leaves sockets for all three.

Architecture — a governance pipeline inside semantic-mcp-server

Each stage is a small module with one job and a uniform contract: it receives a GovernanceContext (mutable per-call state) and either enriches it or short-circuits with a decision. Future modules are just new stages.

call_tool(name, args)
   │
   ▼
┌──────────────────────── governance pipeline ────────────────────────┐
│  ctx = GovernanceContext(tool, intent, args)                        │
│                                                                     │
│  1. identity.py    resolve caller → {role, region}   [swap: authN]  │
│  2. authz.py       role ∈ tool.allowed_roles?                       │
│  3. facts.py       precheck row ∪ args ∪ caller ∪ metrics           │
│  4. rules.py       evaluate business rules → fired[] [swap: OPA]    │
│  5. decide.py      precedence: block > approval > allow             │
│  6. masking.py     restricted-field masking for reads               │
│  7. trace.py       append decision trace (always runs)              │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
   │ allowed → execute template (reads; writes behind --enable-writes)
   │ approval_required → return approver_roles + reasons (decision-only)
   │ blocked → return reasons

Module contracts (the modularity)

@dataclass
class GovernanceContext:
    intent: str
    args: dict            # agent-supplied params only
    caller: Caller | None # set by identity stage
    facts: dict           # built up by facts stage
    evaluated: list[RuleOutcome]   # every rule + fired? + why
    decision: Decision | None      # set once; later stages respect it

class Stage(Protocol):
    def run(self, ctx: GovernanceContext) -> GovernanceContext: ...

The pipeline is an ordered list of Stages — adding token validation later = insert an authn stage at position 0; switching to OPA later = replace rules.py with an adapter implementing the same Stage protocol. Nothing else changes.

